{"key":"processedPost-17397944","value":{"id":17397944,"first":17394026,"last":17400912,"when":1355618636,"utime":"12/16/12 02:43 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /> A fully colonized cake does not show even the slightest mark or indentation.&nbsp; It's really as if the shroom was never there. <br /></blockquote><br /><br />This is entirely strain dependent.&nbsp; <br /><br />Some strains are firmly attached to the substrate and others only have a tiny attachment point and the mushrooms twist off easily.&nbsp; Strains in which the fruits are firmly attached to the substrate will suffer considerable damage to the cake or casing layer if they're ripped out.&nbsp; <br /><br />Obviously one needs to evaluate conditions to determine which way will cause the least damage.&nbsp; The stumps left over from picking firmly attached fruits do not rot.&nbsp; However, a divot in the substrate from ripping out a large chunk is almost guaranteed to have green mold before the next flush finishes.<br />RR","title":"Re: Whats seriously the best way to pick muchrooms?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}